   Had we chosen the second as our unit of time, we would have obtained
   Mass and energy are therefore essentially alike; they are only
   different expressions for the same thing. The mass of a body [Pg 49] is
   not a constant; it varies with changes in its energy.[27][11] We see
   from the last of equations (43) that becomes infinite when approaches
   1, the velocity of light. If we develop in powers of , we obtain, The
   second term of this expansion corresponds to the kinetic energy of the
   material particle in classical mechanics.

   [28][11]The emission of energy in radioactive processes is evidently
   connected with the fact that the atomic weights are not integers.
   Attempts have been made to draw conclusions from this concerning the
   structure and stability of the atomic nuclei.

